Problem 2: Choropleth Maps of Unemployment Rates (60 points)

This problem will ask you to make a couple of different choropleth maps; one map will display state-level information, and one plot will display county-level information. This will require you to do some basic data manipulation and aggregation, which is a very common skill to utilize in spatial data specifically and data science in general.

  1. (5pts) Before we dig into the data and start making plots, please read this short article, which discusses a “dirty little secret that data journalists aren’t telling you” about choropleth maps. After you read the article, discuss in 2-4 sentences what you learned from the article, and mention at least one specific R function you can use to reflect what you learned from the article when making choropleth maps.

From the article, we can see that seemingly rational methods of data visualization may not be the most effective way of presenting data. Even though dividing up a full range of data for a variable into equally sized bins might seem like a good idea, this method can be misleading if there are several extreme outliers or if a small number of bins have a disproportionately large/small number of observations. When considering how to visualize big distinctions in the data, like positive versus negative growth, it is often useful to use a bivariate color distribution to emphasize the distinction compared to using a single color gradient. More generally, it’s worthwhile to think carefully about the color scheme we use in our maps - color schemes should be easy to read (i.e., it should be easy to differentiate high-value regions from low-value regions) while also not being misleading (e.g., the same color shouldn’t represent meaningfully different values, such as positive and negative values having the same color). The R function scale_fill_gradient2() gives us a lot of flexibility for implementing color schemes, and we should use this function carefully.

  1. (10pts) In Part B, you made a choropleth map of the average unemployment rate for each state, where “average” is defined as just the simple average across all counties in that state. However, different counties will likely have very different population sizes, and thus it might not be appropriate to take just a simple average across all counties. Instead, we can consider a weighted average, where we upweigh counties with large population sizes and downweigh counties with low population sizes. In this case, the weighted average for a given state is defined as:

\[ \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n P_i U_i }{\sum_{i=1}^n P_i } \]

where \(P_i\) is the TotalPop for county \(i\) and \(U_i\) is the Unemployment for county \(i\). Thus, when you computed the simple average in Part B, you instead set \(P_i = 1\) in the above definition of the weighted mean, thereby giving each county equal weight when computing the average.

For this part, again make a choropleth map showing the average unemployment rate at the state level. However, define average unemployment rate as the weighted average across counties, instead of the simple average. To do this, you should be able to just copy-and-paste your code from Part B, alter it slightly, and define the average unemployment rate as a weighted average instead of a simple average.

#Compute the weighted mean across counties:
acs.stateWeightedMean = acs %>% group_by(State) %>%
  summarize(meanUnemployment = sum(TotalPop*Unemployment)/sum(TotalPop) )

#In order to match the state data, we need to convert
#the state name to lower case in the ACS dataset.
acs.stateWeightedMean$State = tolower(acs.stateWeightedMean$State)

#Now we can merge the two datasets
acs.stateWeightedMean.merged = state.data %>% left_join(acs.stateWeightedMean, by = c("region" = "State"))

# Plot of states, colored by average unemployment rate
ggplot(acs.stateWeightedMean.merged) +
  geom_polygon(aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, fill = meanUnemployment), 
               color = "black") + 
  scale_fill_gradient2(high = "darkred", low = "darkblue", 
                       mid = "white", midpoint = median(acs.stateMean$meanUnemployment)) +
  theme_void() +
  coord_map("polyconic") + 
  labs(title = "Average Unemployment Rate by State",
       fill = "Unemployment Rate (%)") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

In this part, we will show how to complement our findings about the state-level map in Part B with a dendrogram and a visual randomization test. You only had to do one of these two approaches for your submission, but I wanted to demonstrate both approaches here.

First we will make a dendrogram, where leaf labels list the state and are colored by a geographic region of the US. To make a dendrogram based on the unemployment rate, we follow the same procedure we’ve seen before: Scale the outcome variable (in this case, unemployment rate), create a distance matrix, run hierarchical clustering, and create a dendrogram.

#scaling our outcome variable
unemp.scaled = acs.stateMean$meanUnemployment/sd(acs.stateMean$meanUnemployment)
#creating our distance matrix
unemp.dist = dist(unemp.scaled)
#run hierarchical clustering
unemp.hc = hclust(unemp.dist, method = "complete")
#convert to a dendrogram type object
unemp.dend = as.dendrogram(unemp.hc)

Using the set() function, we can also easily change the leaf labels to the names of each state:

library(dendextend)
unemp.dend = set(unemp.dend, "labels", acs.stateMean$State, order_value = T)

At this point, we can plot an interesting dendrogram, with leaf labels corresponding to each state:

plot(unemp.dend)

However, it is difficult to ascertain geographic regions from the leaf labels alone: We have to go through every leaf label and think about whether the states clustered together are geographically close together (which may be especially hard to do if you’re not super familiar with US geography).

To make the dendrogram more informative, we will color the leaf labels by geographic region. In particular, we will use the state.region object available in the datasets library, as we used in the R demo:

We could also perform a visual randomization test, as we do below.

#It'll be helpful to write a function that automatically
#makes a ggplot for us.
#This is literally the same code we used to generate the
#original areal map above, but for any dataset called "data".
getStateMap.unemp = function(data){
  plot = ggplot(data) +
  geom_polygon(aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, fill = meanUnemployment), 
               color = "black") + 
  scale_fill_gradient2(high = "darkred", low = "darkblue", 
                       mid = "white", midpoint = 7.86) +
  theme_void() +
  coord_map("polyconic")
  return(plot)
}

#Now we're going to permute (i.e., "shuffle") the outcomes a few times.
#number of randomizations/permutations/shuffles:
rands = 9

plotList = list(length = rands)
for(r in 1:rands){
  #create a "randomized" dataset
  acs.stateMean.merged.rand = acs.stateMean.merged
  #shuffle the outcomes
  acs.stateMean.merged.rand$meanUnemployment = sample(acs.stateMean.merged.rand$meanUnemployment)
  #create the plot and store it
  plotList[[r]] = getStateMap.unemp(acs.stateMean.merged.rand)
}

#pick a random entry of plotList to be the "real" plot
plotList[[sample(1:rands, size = 1)]] = getStateMap.unemp(acs.stateMean.merged)

#plot all the plots together
library(gridExtra)
## 
## Attaching package: 'gridExtra'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     combine
grid.arrange(plotList[[1]], plotList[[2]], plotList[[3]],
             plotList[[4]], plotList[[5]], plotList[[6]],
             plotList[[7]], plotList[[8]], plotList[[9]],
             nrow = 3)

I would say that, arguably, the “real” map still stands out, because it has some distinct clustering of blue values (i.e., low unemployment) in the center of the map, and we don’t see this kind of clustering (just by chance) in the other maps. Thus, I would argue that this randomization suggests that the unemployment rates are significantly non-random across states, i.e., there is a geographic relationship among unemployment rates. [However, you may well have come up with a different conclusion, depending on the maps you produced just by chance from your randomization test.].
